const indianPhilosophy:ArticleSection[]=[
  section('overview','An umbrella for many arguments about knowledge and liberation',[
    'Indian philosophy names a long, multilingual field of argument rather than one religion, doctrine, or national essence. Its participants include Brahmanical, Buddhist, Jain, materialist, skeptical, devotional, and other traditions whose institutions and commitments often conflict. They ask what makes cognition reliable, whether a self persists, what kinds of things are real, how language refers, why action has consequences, what suffering is, and whether liberation is possible. Some connect inquiry to ritual or revelation; others criticize those authorities. Some defend enduring selves, substances, or a creator; others reject one or all of them. The umbrella is useful only if it preserves these disagreements.',
    'Many classical authors treat philosophy as a disciplined practice with practical stakes. A mistaken account of self or action may sustain attachment and suffering; a reliable account may guide ethical conduct, contemplation, debate, or release. Yet “liberation” is not one shared conclusion. Jain liberation concerns freeing an individual soul from karmic matter, Buddhist paths deny a permanent self, and Vedānta schools disagree about how self, world, and ultimate reality are related. Nyāya emphasizes warranted cognition and realist analysis; Mīmāṃsā defends ritual interpretation and the authority of the Veda; materialist voices challenge rebirth and supersensible claims. Indian philosophy is the conversation among such positions, not their reduction to a single spiritual message.'
  ],['buddhist-philosophy','jainism','vedanta','epistemology','metaphysics'],['buddha','mahavira','kanada','patanjali','shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],['Upanishads','Nyāya Sutra','Tattvartha Sutra','Brahma Sutra']),
  section('historical-development','Texts, schools, commentaries, and changing institutions',[
    'The earliest Vedic materials developed over many centuries and include hymns, ritual interpretation, speculation, and reflection on cosmic and human order. The Upanishads pursue questions about knowledge, personhood, death, rebirth, and ultimate reality in multiple voices rather than presenting one uniform system. From roughly the middle of the first millennium BCE, renunciant movements, including Buddhist and Jain communities, advanced competing accounts of karma, discipline, self, and release. Court, monastery, household, temple, and debate hall all became sites of intellectual production. Oral teaching and memorization remained important even as terse sutras, verse treatises, narrative works, and extensive commentaries created durable lineages of interpretation.',
    'Classical schools were not born fully formed at one date. Nyāya, Vaisheshika, Samkhya, Yoga, Mīmāṃsā, and Vedānta developed through layered texts and later systematization, while Buddhist and Jain philosophers participated in the same argumentative worlds. Authors debated perception, inference, testimony, absence, universals, causation, language, and the conditions of liberation. Later thinkers wrote in Sanskrit, Pali, Prakrits, Tamil, Persian, and many vernaculars; philosophical work also moved through devotional movements, Islamic intellectual cultures, colonial education, reform, and anticolonial politics. Modern categories such as “Hinduism” and “Indian philosophy” organize this history retrospectively. They can aid orientation, but they should not erase regional, sectarian, linguistic, and institutional change.'
  ],['buddhist-philosophy','jainism','vedanta','logic','philosophy-of-religion'],['buddha','mahavira','kanada','patanjali'],['Vedas','Upanishads','Yoga Sutra','Vaisheshika Sutra']),
  section('methods-and-concepts','Reliable cognition, argument, action, and release',[
    'Pramāṇa means a source or means of reliable cognition, though traditions disagree about which means there are and how their reliability is established. Perception and inference are widely discussed; testimony, comparison, postulation, and cognition of absence receive different treatment. The question is not simply whether reason or experience wins. It is how a cognition arises, what object it presents, how error is distinguished from success, and whether one cognition can certify another without regress. Nyāya philosophers defend a robust realism and procedures of inference and debate. Buddhist epistemologists reconstruct perception, inference, and language around momentariness and exclusion. Mīmāṃsā authors develop sophisticated accounts of linguistic understanding and Vedic authority. Jain accounts place knowledge within a many-sided reality and the limitations of ordinary standpoints.',
    'Karma likewise carries different metaphysical burdens. It can describe morally structured action and consequence, but Buddhist, Jain, and Brahmanical theories disagree about what continues across lives, how causal traces work, and what removes bondage. Dharma can refer to duty, teaching, law, quality, or an element of experience depending on context; translating every occurrence as one English word invites confusion. Moksha, nirvana, and kaivalya are not interchangeable labels for generic enlightenment. Their meanings depend on rival accounts of agency, selfhood, reality, and practice. Careful study therefore begins by asking which school is speaking, what genre it uses, and which opponent its technical vocabulary addresses.'
  ],['epistemology','logic','buddhist-epistemology','jainism','vedanta'],['kanada','patanjali','dignaga','dharmakirti'],['Nyāya Sutra','Yoga Sutra','Tattvartha Sutra']),
  section('self-and-reality','Rival ontologies of persons, substances, moments, and dependence',[
    'Debates about the self illustrate the field’s genuine plurality. Upanishadic texts explore relations between atman, life, consciousness, and brahman without yielding one simple formula. Advaita Vedānta argues that liberating knowledge discloses nonduality, while Vishishtadvaita and Dvaita defend enduring distinctions in different ways. Samkhya distinguishes many conscious purushas from material prakriti; Yoga adapts this framework to disciplined practice. Nyāya defends enduring selves known through inference and the organization of cognition. Jainism affirms a plurality of living souls whose capacities are obscured by karmic bondage. Buddhist traditions reject a permanent, independent self while offering several analyses of persons, continuity, and conventional designation.',
    'Ontological arguments extend far beyond selfhood. Vaisheshika classifies substances, qualities, motions, universals, particularities, and inherence; its atomism is embedded in its own theory of categories and should not be called modern physics in ancient dress. Buddhist Abhidharma analyzes events and factors of experience, while Madhyamaka challenges claims that anything possesses independent intrinsic nature. Vedānta commentators interpret scriptural claims about brahman, world, causation, and dependence differently. These positions cannot be arranged on a simple scale from “spiritual” to “material.” Each combines an inventory of what exists with a theory of explanation, error, cognition, and the transformations demanded for liberation.'
  ],['metaphysics','ontology','buddhist-philosophy','jainism','vedanta'],['kanada','buddha','shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],['Vaisheshika Sutra','Upanishads','Brahma Sutra']),
  section('language-and-reasoning','How words, inferences, and debates do philosophical work',[
    'Indian philosophers developed formal and informal resources for public reasoning. Nyāya accounts of inference analyze a reason, a property to be established, examples, and the dependable relation that licenses the move. Debate manuals classify productive discussion, eristic tactics, fallacious reasons, and points of defeat. These practices were not identical to Aristotelian syllogistic, even when translators use familiar words such as logic or proposition. Their characteristic structures grew from local pedagogies and controversies. Buddhist authors such as Dignāga and Dharmakīrti revise inference around the relation between a reason and what it proves, while Jain authors use conditional predication to mark the standpoint under which a claim is warranted.',
    'Philosophy of language is equally central. Mīmāṃsā and grammarian traditions ask whether words primarily convey universals, individuals, actions, or sentence meaning; whether meaning is composed from independently connected words or grasped first as a sentence unity; and how linguistic knowledge can be authoritative. Buddhist apoha theory explains conceptual content through exclusion rather than a real universal shared by all instances. Vedānta schools dispute how apparently conflicting scriptural passages should be interpreted and what language can reveal about brahman. These are not preliminary language puzzles beside the “real” spiritual teaching. They determine what counts as knowledge, which texts can guide practice, and how philosophical disagreement can be stated at all.'
  ],['logic','philosophy-of-language','buddhist-epistemology','vedanta'],['dignaga','dharmakirti','shankara','ramanuja'],['Nyāya Sutra','Brahma Sutra']),
  section('figures-and-texts','A map of representative voices without a single canon',[
    'No short list can stand for the whole field, but representative texts make its arguments visible. The Upanishads and Bhagavad Gita became major sources for Vedānta and other Brahmanical reflection, while the Brahma Sutra generated competing commentarial traditions. The Nyāya Sutra organizes inquiry, inference, debate, and sources of knowledge. The Vaisheshika Sutra, associated with Kanada, develops categories and a realist natural philosophy. Patanjali’s Yoga Sutra systematizes a path of disciplined attention within a framework related to Samkhya. These works are layered and historically difficult to date; the names attached to them do not always identify a modern-style single author whose biography is securely known.',
    'Mahavira is revered as the twenty-fourth tirthankara of the present Jain cycle, not a creator of Jain teaching from nothing. The Buddha anchors Buddhist lineages whose texts, schools, and philosophies developed across regions and centuries. Shankara, Ramanuja, and Madhva are major Vedānta commentators and systematizers, not founders of Vedānta itself. Their disagreements show why “Hindu philosophy” cannot be treated as a synonym for Advaita. Adding Buddhist philosophers such as Nāgārjuna, Dignāga, and Dharmakīrti, Jain scholastics beyond Mahavira, and the many authors of Nyāya, Mīmāṃsā, grammar, Tantra, and vernacular traditions reveals a distributed intellectual history rather than a parade of isolated sages.'
  ],['jainism','vedanta','buddhist-philosophy','buddhist-epistemology'],['mahavira','buddha','kanada','patanjali','nagarjuna','dignaga','dharmakirti','shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],['Bhagavad Gita','Yoga Sutra','Brahma Sutra','Root Verses on the Middle Way']),
  section('internal-debates','Authority, causation, God, ethics, and the paths to freedom',[
    'Disagreement over authority was persistent. Mīmāṃsā philosophers defend the beginningless Veda and analyze its injunctions, whereas Buddhists and Jains reject Vedic authority and develop their own canons and argumentative standards. The labels astika and nastika are sometimes translated as orthodox and heterodox, but that translation can mislead. In many classificatory settings they mark acceptance or rejection of Vedic authority, not belief versus atheism, moral respectability, or membership in one religion. Even this usage changes by author and period. It is usually clearer to name a tradition’s actual commitments than to make the pair carry more historical unity than it can bear.',
    'Causation, agency, and liberation produce further divisions. Does an effect preexist in its cause, arise as something new, depend on conditions without intrinsic production, or express divine governance? Can action bind an enduring self if the self is changeless? Can continuity and responsibility be explained without such a self? Is liberation achieved primarily through knowledge, disciplined action, devotion, meditation, ascetic restraint, divine grace, or some ordered combination? Schools also debate whether a creator God is necessary, whether testimony is intrinsically warranted, and whether universals are real. The recurring topics do not make the answers interchangeable; they provide shared sites where opponents refine their distinct systems.'
  ],['philosophy-of-religion','epistemology','metaphysics','buddhist-philosophy','jainism','vedanta'],['buddha','mahavira','shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],['Bhagavad Gita','Brahma Sutra']),
  section('misunderstandings','Avoiding the single spiritual wisdom story',[
    'The first misunderstanding is that Indian philosophy teaches that everything is one. That claim resembles some Advaita formulations only after substantial qualification, and it contradicts pluralist, dualist, realist, Jain, Buddhist, and materialist positions. A second mistake treats every school as a religion that replaces argument with revelation. Many authors defend testimony, but they also construct detailed inferences, objections, semantic theories, and rules of debate; others deny the relevant revelation. The opposite mistake extracts arguments from their ethical and soteriological settings as though liberation, discipline, and community were decorative. Intellectual rigor and transformative practice frequently belong to the same project.',
    'Another distortion calls the entire field mystical, timeless, or indifferent to ordinary life. Indian philosophers wrote about politics, law, medicine, grammar, perception, emotion, obligation, violence, and institutional authority as well as ultimate reality. “Ancient wisdom” marketing often combines yoga, Buddhism, Tantra, and Vedānta into a modern therapeutic blend while hiding their disagreements. Responsible comparison also resists easy equations: moksha is not simply salvation, karma is not cosmic revenge, dharma is not one fixed moral law, and Buddhist no-self is not Hume’s bundle theory under another name. Comparison can clarify a problem, but only after goals, genres, institutions, and technical vocabularies remain visible.'
  ],['indian-philosophy','buddhist-philosophy','jainism','vedanta'],['patanjali','shankara','buddha'],[]),
  section('modern-relevance','Living arguments in ethics, knowledge, identity, and interpretation',[
    'These traditions remain living sources of thought, worship, discipline, and controversy rather than relics available for unrestricted philosophical borrowing. Jain nonviolence informs ethical reflection on food, animals, ecology, and political action, though its ascetic foundations are more demanding than a general preference for kindness. Yoga circulates globally through practices often detached from its philosophical histories. Buddhist and Vedānta ideas shape contemporary debates over consciousness, selfhood, and well-being, but scientific or therapeutic adaptations do not automatically confirm their classical metaphysics. Diasporic communities, monastic institutions, universities, translators, and reform movements all participate in deciding how inherited texts speak now.',
    'The history also helps contemporary epistemology. Accounts of testimony, disagreement, inference, absence, and linguistic understanding broaden the archive of theories without serving as exotic analogies for European debates. Many-sidedness can encourage epistemic humility without making truth relative; Buddhist critiques of self can challenge assumptions about ownership and persistence without settling neuroscience; Vedānta arguments can test what dependence and consciousness mean without becoming a shortcut to idealism. Decolonizing a curriculum therefore requires more than adding a representative “Eastern view.” It requires teaching arguments in enough depth that they can disagree with one another and reshape the questions used to organize philosophy.'
  ],['ethics','epistemology','philosophy-of-mind','jainism','vedanta','buddhist-philosophy'],['mahavira','patanjali','shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],[]),
  section('reading-path','A staged route through debates rather than a sampler of slogans',[
    'Begin with a historically guided selection of early Upanishads and several discourses attributed to the Buddha, then add portions of a Jain overview or the Tattvartha Sutra. Ask the same limited questions of each: what is a person, what binds or harms, what kind of knowledge transforms, and what practice follows? Next read the Bhagavad Gita as a multivocal work about action, knowledge, devotion, and duty, not as the single creed of Hinduism. Add selected Yoga Sutra passages and an introduction to Nyāya inference or Vaisheshika categories. Reliable secondary guidance is essential because translations often use the same English term for concepts with different argumentative roles.',
    'At the intermediate stage, follow one controversy across schools. For selfhood, compare Buddhist no-self arguments, Nyāya defenses of an enduring knower, Jain soul theory, and Vedānta interpretations of atman. For language, compare Mīmāṃsā testimony, Buddhist exclusion, and Vedānta scriptural interpretation. For metaphysics, examine causation or universals rather than asking which tradition is most “spiritual.” Then read Shankara, Ramanuja, and Madhva on one shared passage to see commentary produce real disagreement. Keep a glossary that records the school and context for each term. The goal is not a final synthesis but the ability to identify a claim, its warrant, its opponent, and its practical stakes.'
  ],['indian-philosophy','jainism','vedanta','buddhist-philosophy','buddhist-epistemology','logic'],['buddha','mahavira','kanada','patanjali','shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],['Upanishads','Bhagavad Gita','Tattvartha Sutra','Yoga Sutra','Brahma Sutra'])
];

const jainism:ArticleSection[]=[
  section('overview','Liberation through nonviolence, discipline, and careful knowing',[
    'Jainism is a living religious and philosophical tradition centered on the liberation of living beings from karmic bondage. It joins a demanding ethic of nonviolence with metaphysics, cosmology, epistemology, logic, ascetic discipline, lay practice, ritual, and community. Jains affirm a plurality of souls whose capacities for knowledge and bliss are obscured by karma. Karma here is not merely a moral score or metaphor for consequences: classical Jain thinkers describe a subtle material bondage attracted and sustained by embodied action and passion. Liberation requires stopping new influx and shedding accumulated karma through right view, right knowledge, and right conduct.',
    'Mahavira is revered as the twenty-fourth tirthankara, a teacher who renews and transmits a path rather than inventing it as a modern founder would. Jain accounts place him within an immense cosmic history and preserve a traditional chronology whose relationship to modern historical reconstruction is disputed. Parshvanatha, the twenty-third tirthankara, is also central to accounts of the pre-Mahavira community. Jain identity is internally diverse: Digambara and Svetambara traditions differ over texts, monastic practice, clothing, liberation, and aspects of biography, while lay and mendicant forms of discipline differ in degree. A philosophical account must therefore avoid turning one lineage or ideal into the whole tradition.'
  ],['indian-philosophy','ethics','metaphysics'],['mahavira'],['Acaranga Sutra','Tattvartha Sutra']),
  section('historical-development','Tirthankara lineages, communities, councils, and scholastic systems',[
    'Jain tradition situates Mahavira within a lineage of twenty-four ford-makers who show beings a passage across rebirth. Historical scholarship usually places Jain and Buddhist renunciant communities within the social and intellectual transformations of the first millennium BCE, when teachers debated sacrifice, household obligation, asceticism, karma, and release. Mahavira’s precise dates remain contested, and traditional dates should be presented as traditional rather than silently converted into certainty. Early communities transmitted teachings orally in Prakrit languages. Over time, monastic lineages, lay patrons, pilgrimage centers, narrative literature, commentaries, and philosophical debate sustained Jain life across different regions of India.',
    'The Digambara and Svetambara traditions preserve different accounts of the canon and the circumstances of division. The Svetambara Agamas and Digambara claims about the loss of original scripture cannot be merged into one neutral canon story. Umasvati or Umasvami’s Tattvartha Sutra became authoritative across sectarian lines, though traditions interpret its authorship and details differently. Later figures developed logic, epistemology, ethics, grammar, literature, and polemic in conversation with Buddhist and Brahmanical rivals. Colonial classification, print, reform, migration, and global advocacy transformed how Jainism was represented. Today both mendicant orders and lay communities negotiate inherited disciplines within urban, professional, diasporic, and ecological settings.'
  ],['indian-philosophy','buddhist-philosophy','ethics'],['mahavira','buddha'],['Tattvartha Sutra']),
  section('nonviolence','Ahimsa as attention to living beings and the causes of harm',[
    'Ahimsa, nonviolence or non-harming, is not simply a prohibition against spectacular violence. It reorganizes movement, speech, diet, work, possession, and attention around the vulnerability of living beings. Jain classifications recognize life in forms that ordinary perception can overlook, and mendicant discipline seeks to reduce injury with extraordinary care. Intention matters, but avoidable bodily harm is not made harmless merely by good motives. Monastics undertake great vows, while laypeople adopt limited vows calibrated to household responsibilities. This difference does not create two unrelated ethics; it organizes degrees of restraint within a shared orientation toward liberation.',
    'Nonviolence is connected to truthfulness, non-stealing, sexual restraint, and non-possession. Speech can injure, possessiveness can intensify passion, and consumption can enlist a person in dispersed harm. Jain ethical reasoning therefore asks not only “Did I intend harm?” but also “What beings and dependencies does this practice involve, and how can violence be reduced?” The ideal is demanding and internally debated. Survival itself involves harm, social action can create conflicting responsibilities, and modern economies conceal causal chains. Jain ethics does not supply an effortless purity test; it supplies practices of vigilance, confession, restraint, and gradual reduction whose ascetic purpose should not be diluted into generic lifestyle advice.'
  ],['ethics','indian-philosophy'],['mahavira'],['Acaranga Sutra']),
  section('karma-and-liberation','Soul, bondage, restraint, and release',[
    'Jain metaphysics distinguishes living souls from nonliving realities such as matter, the media or conditions of motion and rest, space, and time. A soul is intrinsically capable of unlimited knowledge, perception, energy, and bliss, yet karmic matter binds it through activities infused by passions such as anger, pride, deceit, and greed. Embodied beings occupy different forms according to complex karmic histories. This is neither a doctrine of divine punishment nor the idea that victims deserve whatever happens to them. It is a causal and moral cosmology without a creator judge, and its explanatory claims must be understood within that system rather than translated into the slogan that the universe pays everyone back.',
    'The path interrupts bondage through stopping karmic influx and removing existing karma. Right faith or view, right knowledge, and right conduct form three mutually supporting jewels. Ascetic practices, meditation, careful conduct, repentance, and detachment weaken the passions that bind. Liberation is the soul’s release from karmic embodiment, not its absorption into a universal consciousness. This pluralism distinguishes Jain liberation from Advaita nonduality and from Buddhist no-self. The contrast should not become a ranking of which view is more logical or compassionate; it is a disagreement about what a being is, what continuity requires, why bondage occurs, and what freedom would have to change.'
  ],['metaphysics','indian-philosophy','vedanta','buddhist-philosophy'],['mahavira','shankara','buddha'],['Tattvartha Sutra']),
  section('many-sidedness','Anekāntavāda, viewpoints, and epistemic humility',[
    'Anekāntavāda holds that complex reality is many-sided and cannot ordinarily be captured exhaustively by one unqualified assertion. Objects possess multiple aspects and stand in changing relations; finite knowers approach them under particular descriptions, purposes, and conditions. The doctrine grows within Jain realism, not a skeptical claim that no truth exists. A statement may accurately express one aspect while becoming false when treated as complete or detached from its conditions. This allows Jain philosophers to diagnose rival positions as one-sided without assuming that all rivals are equally correct.',
    'Nayavada analyzes partial standpoints or modes of approach. A practical description, a generic classification, and a moment-focused account may each disclose something while answering different questions. Intellectual humility follows because a knower should state the respect in which a claim holds and remain alert to excluded aspects. Yet humility is disciplined by noncontradiction, evidence, and the structure of what is known. Anekāntavāda does not mean that every opinion is true, that expertise is irrelevant, or that incompatible actions are equally acceptable. Jain authors use it to argue for their own ontology and to criticize absolutized claims. Its tolerance is an achievement of qualified judgment, not indifference to truth.'
  ],['epistemology','logic','indian-philosophy'],['mahavira'],[]),
  section('conditional-predication','Syādvāda and the discipline of qualified assertion',[
    'Syādvāda is commonly explained through seven forms of conditional predication. The particle syat marks that a statement is asserted “in some respect” or under appropriate conditions. One may say that something is, is not, both is and is not in different respects, is indescribable under a given combination, and formulate further qualified combinations. The scheme does not casually affirm a contradiction in the same respect, time, and sense. It directs attention to standpoint, mode, place, time, and the limits of a single predication. English summaries that render syat merely as “maybe” can make the method sound indecisive when its point is logical discipline.',
    'The relationship among syādvāda, anekāntavāda, and nayavada is often described as one among many-sided reality, partial standpoints, and qualified expression. Historical authors formulate the details differently, so the triad should not be treated as one timeless diagram accepted without dispute. In debate, conditional predication offers a way to preserve insights from rival claims while showing where each overreaches. It is not identical to modern many-valued logic, perspectivism, or relativism, though comparison with those theories can generate questions. The Jain framework belongs to a realist, ethical, and liberative project in which how one asserts can itself resist the violence of dogmatic simplification.'
  ],['logic','epistemology','philosophy-of-language'],[],[]),
  section('figures-and-texts','Canonical teachers and a long scholastic conversation',[
    'Teachings associated with Mahavira are preserved through community transmission rather than writings authored by him. The Acaranga Sutra presents ascetic conduct and nonviolence in the Svetambara canon. The Sutrakritanga addresses rival views and discipline. The Tattvartha Sutra offers a concise Sanskrit system of reality, knowledge, karma, ethics, and liberation that is studied across major Jain divisions. These texts require guides attentive to canon history and sectarian interpretation. Reading a translated aphorism alone can conceal the commentarial work needed to specify its terms.',
    'Later Jain philosophers elaborated many-sidedness, proof, language, and debate in exchange with Buddhist and Brahmanical thinkers. Haribhadra compared systems and wrote on yoga; Akalanka made major contributions to logic and epistemology; Hemacandra worked across philosophy, grammar, literature, and religious instruction; Yasovijaya brought analytic precision to early modern Jain intellectual life. A branch page cannot attach every historical author to a profile record, but it should make the long tradition visible. Mahavira is canonical and indispensable, yet Jain philosophy is not exhausted by reconstructing his life or repeating several vows.'
  ],['indian-philosophy','logic','buddhist-epistemology'],['mahavira'],['Acaranga Sutra','Tattvartha Sutra']),
  section('internal-debates-and-neighbors','Sectarian difference and philosophical contest',[
    'Digambara and Svetambara communities disagree about canon, mendicant clothing and possession, aspects of Mahavira’s biography, and whether women can attain liberation in a female body, among other questions. Neither label names a single unchanging position, and further lineages complicate the map. Lay ethics also raises debates about how vows apply to commerce, agriculture, professions, technology, and political participation. The ascetic ideal can critique accumulation while depending materially on lay support. These tensions are not evidence that the ethic fails; they are the lived problems through which a rigorous ideal is interpreted.',
    'Jain thinkers contest Buddhist accounts of momentariness and no-self, defending persistent souls and a reality with enduring and changing aspects. They dispute Vedānta accounts of an ultimate brahman and criticize creator theologies, while Brahmanical and Buddhist opponents challenge Jain pluralism and karma theory. Similar words do not make the systems equivalent: Jain ahimsa, Buddhist compassion, and Hindu nonviolence arise within different accounts of agency, vow, life, and liberation. Exchanges shaped each tradition’s arguments, so “neighbor” does not mean a sealed civilization politely comparing finished doctrines. It means opponents sharing languages, institutions, examples, and standards while contesting basic reality.'
  ],['buddhist-philosophy','vedanta','indian-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion'],['buddha','shankara','mahavira'],[]),
  section('misunderstandings-and-relevance','Beyond harmlessness, relativism, and a founder story',[
    'Jainism is not simply vegetarianism, although dietary discipline is an important expression of nonviolence. It is not a passive refusal to act, because careful action, generosity, teaching, community support, and self-discipline are required. Mahavira is not best described as the inventor of a new creed; Jain tradition understands him as a tirthankara in an earlier lineage, and his traditional chronology is not historically certain. Anekāntavāda does not declare all opinions equally true, and syādvāda does not license contradiction without qualification. Karma is not fate: anti-fatalistic discipline matters precisely because conduct can alter bondage.',
    'Jain thought speaks forcefully to contemporary questions about animal life, environmental limits, consumption, conflict, and epistemic arrogance. Non-possession challenges identities built around acquisition, while many-sidedness encourages precise listening across disagreement. Still, modern application should not claim that Jain texts anticipated environmental science, vegan activism, or pluralist democracy in their current forms. Those are creative receptions shaped by new institutions and knowledge. The tradition’s contribution is deeper when its ascetic goals and metaphysics remain visible: it asks how ordinary habits enlist us in harm, how certainty can become violent, and whether freedom requires transforming desire rather than merely choosing among available products.'
  ],['ethics','political-philosophy','epistemology','indian-philosophy'],['mahavira'],[]),
  section('reading-path','From ethical orientation to metaphysics and debate',[
    'Begin with a reliable historical overview and selected passages from the Acaranga Sutra on ascetic conduct and care for life. Read them as monastic instruction rather than as a collection of inspirational quotations. Move to accessible selections from the Tattvartha Sutra with commentary, tracking the categories of soul, non-soul, karmic influx, restraint, shedding, bondage, and liberation. Keep separate notes on the great vows and the limited lay vows. This sequence shows how ethics depends on a picture of living beings and causation rather than floating free as a universal maxim.',
    'Next study anekāntavāda, nayavada, and syādvāda through a scholarly introduction that distinguishes historical formulations. Test the sevenfold predication on one changing object, specifying respect and time rather than reciting a list. Then compare one focused controversy: Jain soul theory with Buddhist no-self, Jain many-sided realism with Madhyamaka emptiness, or Jain liberation with a Vedānta account. Do not ask which English slogan is friendliest. Ask what each view treats as real, which cognitions it trusts, why error or bondage arises, and which practices follow. End with modern Jain discussions of animals, ecology, or business ethics while identifying what is adaptation and what is inherited argument.'
  ],['jainism','indian-philosophy','buddhist-philosophy','vedanta','ethics'],['mahavira','buddha','shankara'],['Acaranga Sutra','Tattvartha Sutra'])
];

const vedanta:ArticleSection[]=[
  section('overview','A family of arguments over the end and meaning of the Veda',[
    'Vedānta names a family of traditions that interpret the Upanishads, Brahma Sutra, Bhagavad Gita, and related scriptures in order to explain ultimate reality, selfhood, world, bondage, and liberation. The word evokes the “end” or culmination of the Veda, but it does not identify one doctrine. Advaita defends nonduality, Vishishtadvaita articulates a qualified nondualism centered on a personal God, and Dvaita insists on real differences among God, souls, and matter. Other Vedānta traditions further complicate the map. Their commentators share texts and questions while disagreeing about grammar, revelation, causation, devotion, knowledge, embodiment, and the status of plurality.',
    'Shankara, Ramanuja, and Madhva are major commentators and systematizers, not founders of Vedānta itself. Each inherits earlier exegetical debates and establishes a lineage whose later thinkers refine or contest his positions. Presenting Vedānta as “Shankara’s philosophy” mistakes one influential school for the whole field; presenting all three as saying that every self is divine erases their strongest disagreements. Vedānta is best entered as a history of argued interpretation. A scriptural passage does not arrive with one obvious metaphysics: schools establish rules for reading, reconcile apparently conflicting statements, and show how a reading supports a path of knowledge, devotion, action, grace, or their combination.'
  ],['indian-philosophy','metaphysics','philosophy-of-religion'],['shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],['Upanishads','Bhagavad Gita','Brahma Sutra']),
  section('historical-development','From diverse Upanishads to rival commentarial lineages',[
    'The Upanishads are a layered collection spanning different periods, settings, and voices. They investigate sacrifice, breath, consciousness, personhood, death, and brahman through dialogue, instruction, narrative, and compressed declaration. Later interpreters treat selected Upanishads, the Bhagavad Gita, and the Brahma Sutra as a triple foundation, though the exact canon and hierarchy of passages vary. Badarayana’s Brahma Sutra systematizes interpretive problems in terse aphorisms whose meaning depends heavily on commentary. Vedānta therefore did not begin when one famous commentator discovered a complete doctrine waiting unchanged in the texts. It developed through sustained disputes about how multiple authoritative sources cohere.',
    'Shankara’s eighth-century Advaita commentaries became foundational for a powerful nondual lineage, while earlier teachers and rival interpretations remain important. Ramanuja’s eleventh- and twelfth-century works develop Vishishtadvaita through devotion, divine embodiment, and a realist account of souls and world. Madhva’s thirteenth-century Dvaita defends fundamental difference and the supremacy of Vishnu. Later Vedānta includes Bhedabheda, Nimbarka, Vallabha, Gaudiya Vaishnava, Srivaishnava, Advaita, Dvaita, and other communities with their own texts and practices. In the colonial and modern periods, reformers and global teachers selectively recast Vedānta as universal religion, rational spirituality, nationalism, or philosophy of consciousness. Those receptions matter, but they should not be projected backward as the tradition’s timeless essence.'
  ],['indian-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion'],['shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],['Upanishads','Brahma Sutra']),
  section('shared-problems','Brahman, atman, world, bondage, and liberating knowledge',[
    'Vedānta schools ask how brahman, the ultimate source and ground discussed in scripture, relates to individual selves and the experienced world. They also ask how bondage is possible, what ignorance or karma does, and what liberation changes. Shared vocabulary does not imply shared referents. For Advaita, the deepest truth is nondual brahman, and ignorance underlies superimposed distinctions. For Vishishtadvaita, brahman is the personal Lord whose unity includes real souls and matter as dependent modes or body. For Dvaita, God, souls, and matter are genuinely different, even though all depend on God. “Atman is brahman” therefore cannot be used as an unqualified summary of every school.',
    'Schools also disagree over whether consciousness is the essence of self, an attribute of a persistent soul, or intelligible only through dependence on God. The world may be interpreted as empirically experienced under ignorance, as a real transformation or expression dependent on brahman, or as a genuinely distinct created order. Maya can name divine power, the conditions of appearance, or be framed differently across periods; it does not simply mean that nothing exists. Liberation can involve the removal of ignorance, direct realization, loving service in relation to God, divine grace, freedom from karma, or an eternal relation preserved rather than dissolved. The philosophical work lies in these distinctions.'
  ],['metaphysics','ontology','philosophy-of-mind','philosophy-of-religion'],['shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],['Upanishads','Brahma Sutra']),
  section('advaita','Advaita: nonduality, ignorance, and levels of discourse',[
    'Shankara’s Advaita argues that brahman is nondual and that the innermost self is not ultimately different from it. Ordinary experience presents plurality, agency, and change, but ignorance leads knowers to superimpose properties and distinctions where they do not ultimately belong. Shankara’s famous introductory discussion of superimposition frames error through familiar confusions before extending the analysis to self and not-self. Liberating knowledge removes ignorance; it does not manufacture brahman or turn one finite individual into the cosmic owner of reality. Ethical preparation, disciplined inquiry, and renunciation matter because hearing a formula is not the same as realizing what it means.',
    'Advaita distinguishes levels or orders of discourse so that everyday and scriptural practices are not treated as simply nonexistent. The empirical world is not absolute reality, but it functions within experience and must be navigated responsibly. Interpretive disputes concern how to characterize maya and avidya, where ignorance resides, how one brahman appears as many, and what role action or devotion plays before knowledge. Later Advaitins develop different theories rather than merely repeating Shankara. Comparison with idealism can illuminate questions about appearance and consciousness, but Advaita’s scriptural practices and liberative aim differ from post-Kantian projects. Calling it subjective idealism or “we create reality” is especially misleading.'
  ],['metaphysics','epistemology','indian-philosophy'],['shankara'],['Commentary on the Brahma Sutra','Upadesasahasri']),
  section('vishishtadvaita','Vishishtadvaita: unity qualified by real souls and world',[
    'Ramanuja criticizes an account in which plurality is ultimately explained through beginningless ignorance. His Vishishtadvaita affirms one brahman while treating souls and matter as real and inseparably dependent on the personal God, often described through a body-soul analogy. Brahman is qualified by this ordered plurality rather than stripped of every characteristic. Scriptural passages about unity and passages about difference must be interpreted together. The world is meaningful, embodied service is not merely provisional error, and divine qualities such as knowledge, goodness, and compassion are philosophically and devotionally central.',
    'Liberation involves knowledge and freedom from karma but does not erase the individual into an undifferentiated absolute. The liberated self exists in dependence on God and participates in loving service. Ramanuja gives devotion and surrender a central role while also treating action, discipline, and scriptural knowledge as ordered parts of a path. Grace raises questions about human effort and divine initiative that later Srivaishnava lineages develop differently. Translating Vishishtadvaita as a compromise halfway between monism and dualism misses its own architecture. It is a positive theory of divine unity, embodiment, dependence, and value, built through close interpretation rather than by adjusting a slider between two Western categories.'
  ],['philosophy-of-religion','metaphysics','ethics'],['ramanuja'],['Sri Bhasya','Vedarthasamgraha']),
  section('dvaita','Dvaita: real difference, dependence, and divine supremacy',[
    'Madhva’s Dvaita insists on real and enduring differences: between God and individual souls, God and matter, one soul and another, soul and matter, and material things. Vishnu is independent; all other realities are dependent. This is not Cartesian mind-body dualism and not merely the claim that there are two substances. Dvaita is a theistic pluralist system with its own account of scripture, hierarchy, causation, knowledge, and devotion. Madhva rereads passages that Advaita takes as statements of identity, arguing that the canon consistently supports difference and dependence.',
    'Liberation does not dissolve the soul’s identity. Correct knowledge of God, devotion, grace, and freedom from bondage sustain an eternal relation. Madhva and later Dvaita thinkers criticize Advaita’s account of ignorance: if brahman alone is ultimately real and pure consciousness, they ask how error can arise or where it can be located. They also dispute Vishishtadvaita’s qualified unity. Dvaita doctrines concerning gradations among souls and destiny are difficult and require care rather than apologetic omission. The tradition demonstrates why Vedānta cannot be summarized as nonduality. The same authoritative texts can underwrite an emphatic realism of difference when accompanied by different semantic, theological, and hermeneutic arguments.'
  ],['philosophy-of-religion','metaphysics','indian-philosophy'],['madhva'],['Commentary on the Brahma Sutra','Anuvyakhyana']),
  section('interpretation-and-practice','Why exegesis, reasoning, devotion, and discipline belong together',[
    'Vedānta commentary is not a decorative layer placed over direct mystical experience. Interpreters establish which passages state a central teaching, how context fixes meaning, when figurative interpretation is justified, and how apparently conflicting sentences can be reconciled. They draw on grammar, Mīmāṃsā hermeneutics, epistemology, and debate. Scripture functions as a source of knowledge for realities that ordinary perception and inference cannot independently disclose, but schools disagree about how its authority works and how reasoning supports interpretation. An argument about a pronoun, case ending, or sequence of verses can therefore carry metaphysical consequences.',
    'Practice likewise differs across schools and social histories. Hearing, reflection, and contemplative assimilation are central to Advaita accounts of knowledge; devotion, ritual, surrender, and service are crucial in theistic Vedānta; moral and ritual duties may prepare, express, or partly constitute the path. Questions of caste, gender, renunciation, household life, and access to Vedic learning complicate every simple portrait of universal liberation. Vernacular devotional communities sometimes broaden access while developing their own exclusions. Responsible study recognizes the philosophical content of practice without pretending that canonical institutions were socially neutral.'
  ],['epistemology','philosophy-of-language','philosophy-of-religion','ethics'],['shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],['Bhagavad Gita','Brahma Sutra']),
  section('neighbors-and-debates','Buddhist, Jain, Nyāya, Mīmāṃsā, and intra-Vedānta arguments',[
    'Vedānta develops within a dense Indian field. Its authors dispute Buddhist accounts of no-self, momentariness, and emptiness, but “Buddhist opponent” covers multiple schools and sometimes a stylized position inherited from earlier polemic. Nyāya realists challenge Advaita explanations of error and defend a plurality of knowers and objects. Mīmāṃsā supplies techniques of Vedic interpretation while often emphasizing ritual duty differently from Vedānta’s concern with brahman. Jain thinkers reject a single ultimate brahman and defend many enduring souls. These are not meetings between isolated religions. Thinkers share technical languages and argumentative forms while contesting the authority and meaning of texts.',
    'Within Vedānta, causation is a major fault line. Does the world emerge as a transformation, an appearance, or a dependent reality distinct from its source? If brahman is perfect, how can plurality, suffering, and ignorance be explained? If souls depend completely on God, what grounds responsibility? If liberation needs knowledge, what roles remain for action and devotion? Interpretive arguments about identity statements, divine attributes, and the scope of negation decide more than labels such as monism or dualism reveal. Cross-cultural comparison should begin after reconstructing these questions. Spinoza’s substance, Berkeley’s idealism, or Christian theism may provide contrasts, but none is an English substitute for a Vedānta school.'
  ],['buddhist-philosophy','jainism','epistemology','philosophy-of-religion'],['buddha','mahavira','shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],['Brahma Sutra']),
  section('misunderstandings-and-relevance','Against the idea that Vedānta is one modern perennial philosophy',[
    'Vedānta is not synonymous with Advaita, and Advaita is not the claim that an individual ego can manifest whatever it wants. Maya does not simply mean the physical world is fake. Ramanuja and Madhva are not incomplete steps toward Shankara; they offer rival readings with different accounts of reality and liberation. Nor did Shankara, Ramanuja, or Madhva found Vedānta. Each systematized an inherited commentarial field. “All religions teach the same thing” belongs to particular modern universalizing receptions, not an uncontested conclusion of the classical schools. Such a slogan can obscure traditions whose identities depend on real doctrinal disagreement.',
    'Vedānta remains relevant to philosophy of consciousness, personal identity, metaphysical dependence, religious language, and the relation of reason to revelation. Living communities continue its devotional and interpretive practices, while modern teachers have translated its ideas for anticolonial, nationalist, interreligious, therapeutic, and global audiences. These adaptations can be philosophically creative without being timeless originals. Contemporary readers should also examine social questions about authority and access rather than extracting a frictionless metaphysics from institutions. The most productive relevance comes from allowing the schools to challenge current assumptions: Is consciousness a property or a condition of disclosure? Can dependence preserve difference? What kind of knowledge could transform a life?'
  ],['philosophy-of-mind','metaphysics','philosophy-of-religion','indian-philosophy'],['shankara','ramanuja','madhva'],[]),
  section('reading-path','Reading shared sources through genuinely rival commentaries',[
    'Begin with several early Upanishads in a reliable translation, noting distinct speakers, settings, and teachings instead of collecting identity statements. Read the Bhagavad Gita next, tracking the relations among action, knowledge, devotion, duty, and renunciation. Then use an introduction to the Brahma Sutra to understand why its compressed aphorisms require commentary. At this stage, build a vocabulary for brahman, atman, karma, moksha, bhakti, maya, and ignorance, but record how each text or school uses the term. Do not define the words once for the entire tradition.',
    'Next select one shared scriptural passage and compare Shankara, Ramanuja, and Madhva with scholarly guidance. Read a short independent work by each when available: Shankara’s Upadesasahasri, Ramanuja’s Vedarthasamgraha, and a guided selection from Madhva’s works. Ask five questions: What is ultimately real? Are souls enduring and distinct? What is the world’s status? What causes bondage? What liberates? Continue into later Advaita, Srivaishnava, and Dvaita authors so each school appears as a developing lineage. Finally compare one Vedānta argument with a Buddhist, Jain, or Nyāya opponent, preserving different standards of scripture and proof rather than staging a generic East-West contest.'
  ],['vedanta','indian-philosophy','buddhist-philosophy','jainism','philosophy-of-religion'],['shankara','ramanuja','madhva','buddha','mahavira'],['Upanishads','Bhagavad Gita','Brahma Sutra','Upadesasahasri','Vedarthasamgraha'])
];

